skill-tuning
=============

Original design — not a port
-----------------------------

This skill is an **original design** authored for monkey-skills.
It is **not** a port, fork, or adaptation of any existing skill.

The broader idea of "autonomous skill optimization with git
ratchet" was popularized by `alchaincyf/darwin-skill` (which was
inspired by Andrej Karpathy's `autoresearch`). However, the design
of this skill — Phase B of the Two-Hats split, deliberately
separated from skill-refactor to handle taste-sensitive output via
human judgment — is independent work. Specifically: `darwin-skill`
mixes structural refactoring with output quality evaluation in a
single 8-dim rubric using LLM-as-judge throughout. This skill
recognizes that LLM-as-judge cannot reliably evaluate
taste-sensitive output (verbosity bias, position bias,
self-preference, insensitivity to subtle quality), and routes that
work through human preference capture instead.

Specific design distinctions from `darwin-skill`:

1. **Phase B isolation** — `skill-tuning` only handles
   taste-sensitive A/B; structural refactor goes to
   `skill-refactor`. `darwin-skill` does both in one rubric. The
   split is foundational to avoiding LLM-as-judge / Goodhart drift
   on taste dimensions.
2. **Human-in-loop is non-skippable** — every iteration requires a
   human pick. `darwin-skill`'s "Human in the loop" is between
   skills (review at end); this skill's HITL is per-A/B iteration.
3. **Constitutional pre-filter** — variants violating MUST clauses
   are filtered before human judgment. `darwin-skill` lacks this
   layer; variants are scored without contract floor.
4. **Blind A/B with random label assignment** — position bias
   mitigation. The user does not know which variant is the
   baseline.
5. **4-option capture** — single / multiple / none / refine.
   `darwin-skill` uses a binary keep/revert; the 4-option matches
   the actual decision space humans face on taste judgments.
6. **Preference log as durable RLHF-lite dataset** — every pick is
   logged with full context (label assignment, rejected variants,
   constitutional rejection record, decision time) for future
   self-trained judge training. `darwin-skill` records
   results.tsv but not in preference-pair training format.
7. **Self-trained judge scaffold** — H4 horizon explicitly
   designed for trainable preference model that replaces
   LLM-judge once log is dense (≥1000 entries). `darwin-skill`
   does not have this trajectory.
8. **Verdict vocabulary** — ADOPT / DROP / DEFER / REFINE /
   ESCALATE. Parallels `complexity-critique` /
   `proposal-critique` / `skill-refactor` discipline; differs
   from `darwin-skill`'s keep/revert.
9. **No auto-revert** — unlike `skill-refactor` (which auto-reverts
   on equivalence failure) and `darwin-skill` (which auto-reverts
   on score drop), this skill **does not auto-revert** because
   "score drop" cannot be reliably computed by LLM on taste
   dimensions. Variants ship only on human ADOPT; absence of pick
   = no change.

Inspirations acknowledged
-------------------------

1. Andrej Karpathy — `autoresearch` (https://github.com/karpathy/autoresearch).
   Original "autonomous loop" pattern.

2. alchaincyf — `darwin-skill` (MIT,
   https://github.com/alchaincyf/darwin-skill).
   First application to Claude Agent Skills.

3. monkey-skills' copywriting voice-anchor curation (MIT). The
   golden anchor / constitutional discipline borrows curation
   patterns from voice-anchor work (90 anchors validated via
   N=10 dry runs).

4. RLHF / preference-modeling literature — the preference log →
   trained-judge pipeline draws on Bradley-Terry-style preference
   loss methodology (used in Anthropic / OpenAI preference
   modeling work).

5. Fowler, M. — *Refactoring* (2nd ed, 2018) Two Hats principle.
   Grounds the refactor-vs-feature split that separates
   skill-refactor from skill-tuning at the architectural level.

6. monkey-skills' skill-evolution architecture rationale — the
   Two-Hats split applied to skills, the cost-blind H1-H4 horizons,
   and the trained-judge trajectory.

